Fisheries data

First, we need to download fisheries.csv from this download link and continents.csv from this download link, and save it in the same directory where you downloaded this RMD file. Both RMD and csv file must be in the same directory!

Then, lets load the csv files using read_csv()

library(tidyverse)
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.6.2
## Warning: package 'tibble' was built under R version 3.6.2
## Warning: package 'purrr' was built under R version 3.6.2
## Warning: package 'dplyr' was built under R version 3.6.2
fisheries <- read_csv("fisheries.csv")
continents <- read_csv("continents.csv")
fisheries <- fisheries %>%
  filter(total > 100000)

Join tables

To join the two tables, we used left_join() in the lecture. Thats because we wanted to keep even the observations that have no match in the continents table. Lets try both left_join() and inner_join() this time to see if there is any difference.

fisheries_innerjoin <- inner_join(fisheries, continents)
## Joining, by = "country"
fisheries_leftjoin <- left_join(fisheries, continents)
## Joining, by = "country"

See, the number of rows in fisheries_innerjoin is 79 while that in fisheries_leftjoin is 82. Why? Because inner_join() exclude those countries that had no corresponding continents. To see the countries for which the continent column is missing:

fisheries_innerjoin %>% filter(is.na(continent))
## # A tibble: 0 x 5
## #  with 5 variables: country <chr>, capture <dbl>, aquaculture <dbl>,
## #   total <dbl>, continent <chr>
fisheries_leftjoin %>% filter(is.na(continent))
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
##   country                          capture aquaculture   total continent
##   <chr>                              <dbl>       <dbl>   <dbl> <chr>    
## 1 Democratic Republic of the Congo  237372        3161  240533 <NA>     
## 2 Hong Kong                         142775        4258  147033 <NA>     
## 3 Myanmar                          2072390     1017644 3090034 <NA>

The additional three observations in fisheries_leftjoin are in fact those countries with missing continent values. Since we dont want to lose any data points, we use left_join() and manually fill in those missing values.

fisheries <- fisheries %>%
  left_join(continents) %>%
  mutate(
    continent = case_when(
      country == "Democratic Republic of the Congo" ~ "Africa",
      country == "Hong Kong"                        ~ "Asia",
      country == "Myanmar"                          ~ "Asia",
      TRUE                                          ~ continent
      ),
    aquaculture_perc = aquaculture / total
    )
## Joining, by = "country"

World map

To map the fisheries data, we need this world map data set that contains geographic boundaries of countries. Once again, left-join the fisheries data with this world map.

world_map <- map_data("world") %>%
  mutate(region = case_when(
    region == "UK"           ~ "United Kingdom",
    region == "USA"          ~ "United States",
    subregion == "Hong Kong" ~ "Hong Kong",
    TRUE                     ~ region
    )
  )
fisheries_map <- left_join(fisheries, world_map, 
                           by = c("country" = "region")) #<<

geom_polygon() is used to plot coordinates (longitude and latitude) on map. What we want to do is to plot each country on the map and vary its color based on the level of fishery harvest.

ggplot(fisheries_map, mapping = aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group)) +
  geom_polygon(aes(fill = capture)) +
  scale_fill_distiller(palette="GnBu") +
  theme_minimal()

You can stack up as many layers of map as we want. Lets add another layer to change the color for those countries that are missing in the fisheries data. First, we use the world_map data to draw all countries in lightgray, and then, add the fishery map above on top of that. In this way, the missing countries will be in the color of lightgray rather than simply being missing.

ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(world_map, 
               mapping = aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group), 
               fill = "lightgray") +
  geom_polygon(fisheries_map, 
               mapping = aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, 
                             fill = capture)) +
  scale_fill_distiller(palette="GnBu") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    x = "", y = "",
    title = "Fisheries harvest by capture, 2016",
    subtitle = "Capture measured in tonnes",
    caption = "Source: bit.ly/2VrawTt"
  )
